{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476288"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:44:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:44:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13720"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13720"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.05,0.23,0.17,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57317"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6339"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42776"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"97"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36919"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44166"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57317"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-month-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother. She reports that for the past week, he has been passing three to four mustard-coloured stools per day containing some mucus and streaks of bright red blood. Defaecation seems painful and is associated with increased straining and unsettled behaviour. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has no significant medical history and was born at term. He is exclusively breast fed, is feeding well and gaining weight appropriately. His mother does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 130/min, respiratory rate 40/min, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination is soft and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anal fissure","Necrotising enterocolitis","Cow\u0027s milk protein allergy","Meckel\u0027s diverticulum","Intussusception"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eanal fissure\u003C/strong\u003E. Anal fissures are the most common cause of rectal bleeding in infants. They typically occur in the posterior midline and can cause painful defaecation with small amounts of bright red blood. The mustard-yellow colour and presence of mucus in the stool are normal findings in exclusively breastfed infants and do not indicate pathology. Breastfed infants typically pass frequent, soft, mustard-coloured stools that may contain white \u0027seeds\u0027 and mucus. Constipation is a common underlying cause of anal fissures. Treatment involves stool softeners, barrier creams, and avoidance of constipation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecrotising enterocolitis\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in preterm or unwell infants. However, this infant was born at term, is thriving, and has no signs of sepsis or abdominal distension on examination, making necrotising enterocolitis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECow\u0027s milk protein allergy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause rectal bleeding in infants, even in exclusively breast-fed infants due to maternal dietary intake. However, it is usually associated with other symptoms such as vomiting, diarrhoea, eczema, or failure to thrive, which are absent in this case. While mucus can be present in cow\u0027s milk protein allergy, it is also a normal finding in healthy breastfed infants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgical causes such as \u003Cstrong\u003EMeckel\u0027s diverticulum\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eintussusception\u003C/strong\u003E are important to consider, particularly if the bleeding is profuse or associated with abdominal pain, distension, or bile-stained vomiting. However, this infant appears well with no red flag features on history or examination, making these diagnoses less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anal fissures are the most common cause of rectal bleeding in infants.","Mucus and mustard-coloured stools are normal findings in exclusively breastfed infants.","Painful defaecation with blood streaks suggests anal fissure rather than other causes of rectal bleeding in infants."],"references":["Nishaben Patel, MD, Marsha Kay, MD. Lower gastrointestinal bleeding in children: Causes and diagnostic approach. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/lower-gastrointestinal-bleeding-in-children-causes-and-diagnostic-approach","Chandel K, Jain R, Bhatia A, Saxena AK, Sodhi KS. Bleeding per rectum in pediatric population: A pictorial review. World J Clin Pediatr. 2022 May 9;11(3):270-288. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9134156/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42776"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13720"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42776"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T20:10:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T20:12:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6339"}},